{
  "text": " Materials Discovery can now imagine millions of crystals. Google DeepMind's Jeanne O'Mea proposed 2.2 million. But by late 2023, only 736 had been independently synthesized. The scarce resource is no longer prediction. It is trust. Every stage leaks. Generators omit complex material classes. Universal machine-learned potentials are least reliable at surfaces, vacancies, and defects. And laboratories inherit every upstream error. More activity does not automatically produce more validated materials. Lupin science sits between prediction and synthesis. It measures a predictor's systematic error as a physical field over local atomic environments, corrects that error at runtime, and proves which claims remain inside the evidence boundary. The field is fixed by three standard observables. A fourth surface is held back as a blind test. Across 36 model and material combinations, predicted and measured errors correlate at 0.906, with zero adjustable parameters. Quantitative claims are then sealed as Lean-4 theorems with hash-locked providence. The proof layer has 190 build-locked theorems and zero unfinished proofs. It once rejected a rounded success count, changing 27 improvements to 26. Trust means being able to say no to yourself. The correction deploys beside existing CHGNet or MACE calculators as a LAMPES overlay. In Python, measured overhead is 15.6%. On a blind nickel surface, relative error fell from 9.7% to 1.5%. Users keep their simulators. Lupine makes them more trustworthy. Better materials infrastructure is estimated to create $1.3 to $2.7 billion in annual value for United States industry. Against that scale, Lupin's 36-month budget is about $3.2 million. The investment is not a bet on one material. It is leverage across every screened material. The face-centered cubic field is established. Other structure families and industrial validation remain open work, with explicit go-or-no-go gates. That honesty is the product. The world does not need more predicted crystals. It needs predictions laboratories can act on.",
